Judas's Note:

This will be the last HQ movie I upload that will contain a 640kbps AAC audio track as with further testing and audio comparisons and thorough research, I've determined the peak bitrates to use. At specific levels using the truehd/dts master source to encode from (not the cores), there is a specific point at which higher bitrate encoding of AAC from those sources seriously diminishes. Basically it's mostly &quot;wasted&quot; data being consumed to fill blank spaces, the fidelity, depth and such do not improve at a linear rate beyond this point. To perhaps put more simply, at about 75-85% AAC quality encoding is the peak, going above these values increases the bitrate linear still, but the quality (when thoroughly analyzed) stagnates/stops. The REALLY awesome fact that AAC allows for a floating point bit depth means that there is no need for dithering or keeping a fixed value for the bit depth allowing for pretty much IDENTICAL quality if not easily better quality than most of the constant bit depth/bit rate alternative lossy formats. AAC is smart, very smart. So to finish off, all further HQ encodes will use this peak efficient and best bang for the bit style of encoding which obviously means a few extra 100MB worth of downloading, but being able to directly compete with DTS-HD 1536kbps due to AAC's serious advantages. Not to mention DTS-HD is limited to 5.1 where as AAC's bitrate can increase retaining quality while providing 6.1 and 7.1 or higher channel counts.


